reviews.review_text: Great show Outstanding late fall / early winter 1973 behemoth. Clear, crisp, soundboard. Nothing could be better until CM gets around to redoing it. Clear the Aisles\' part 1 = greatest banter ever! Check out the last few minues of Uncle John's Band for some very healthy Phil, feedback, and space.
*Uncle Johns Band intro* Check out Jer, right there^^, in the boston air.

Cherry Popper First GD concert....sat 8th row, dead center. Got tickets through some kids father who was in the biz. I know it doesn't stand up to some other night but it still stands as one my all time personal favs.....just because. Cool thing was watching the cops try and get people out of the aisles. At one point, the lead guy gets on stage and starts waving his arms like it's all over. The lights came on, too. But the Dead just kept play like nothing was happening. That's when I knew for sure how different these guys were from every other band. A revelation for me that night that has stood the test of time.

12-1-73 This is great like almost every show from Nov. & Dec. '73. Sound quality is very good. I agree that I' love to see this remastered by Charlie Miller. I think the first 3 Tracks are probably the sound check. I wasn't there so I don't know this to be factual.
good show This is a really nice show that seems to be overlooked somewhat. Maybe its because it sandwiched right in between two Dicks Pick. I love the way Casey Jones sounded in 73

was one of the ones in the aisle that night funny hearing this and there rap about the crowded aisles.
thanks to a close friend at Stonehill college me and a buddy from NY got ticks drove up friday  stayed at the College went Saturday with our buddy in a busload  keg of brew onboard and  a dozen or so other Stonehill  students..recall standing in the left aisle up pretty close up never got to our seats..such a privilege  and life highlight to have been in that beautiful Music Hall Theatre for that amazing show
46th ann. Listening on the 46th anniversary i think it is, smokin

great performance meets great recording Love me some Nov / Dec '73 Dead. 
This particular copy id the one I listen to all the time and it doesn't need any remastering imo.
All instruments sound clear, up front and forming a fantastic soundstage. Wide & High baby!
Hardly any hiss but then again, hiss is our friend. We don't fight it, just let it tag along for when you into the song, hiss is the furthest thing from your mind.
Lots to love at this show, this run. Tonight it's the 30 minute Playin'~UJB~Playin'. Jerry is on fire yet patient. Keith is the unsung hero in this sandwich. Wow!
Stay cool friends. Might as well.
tpace
